data.content:
Here's what happened:

## C# 14 Span Overload Resolution Change

In .NET 10 / C# 14, new built-in span conversions cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (which takes `ReadOnlySpan<T>`) instead of `Enumerable.Contains`. Since `MemoryExtensions.Contains` cannot be represented in an expression tree, it throws at runtime when the expression is compiled/interpreted.

## Fix Options

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` to force binding to `Enumerable.Contains`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Any of these forces the compiler to resolve the old `Enumerable.Contains` overload, which is expressible in a LINQ expression tree.
